"response_text": "The mean household initial risk attitude remains fixed at 0.0074 across all 100 steps of the simulation. This metric, representing the average baseline disposition to deviate from recommended livestock numbers, exhibits no temporal variation, maintaining identical values at step 0 and step 100 with zero variance throughout the series. The constancy persists across all 30 simulation runs aggregated in the analysis, with statistical tests revealing no significant increasing or decreasing trends in any observation window. Ihe aggregate mean of approximately 0.0074 suggests a slight collective tendency toward positive deviation from recommendations, though this central tendency masks substantial diversity in baseline risk preferences across the population.\n\nIndividual households or simulation runs display heterogeneous initial risk attitudes distributed across a range from approximately -0.11 to +0.18, yet each maintains its specific constant value throughout the yearly sequences. This indicates that initial risk attitudes are static parameters assigned at initialization that do not evolve through the learning processes or ecological feedbacks occurring during the simulation. \n\nFor decision makers, the immutability of initial risk attitudes implies that heterogeneous risk tolerances constitute a fixed structural constraint in grazing system management. Policies must accommodate this diversity, as households maintain their baseline propensity to accept or avoid risk regarding livestock decisions regardless of social learning opportunities or ecological changes encountered during the simulation period. The presence of both negative (risk-averse) and positive (risk-seeking) values in the population, centered near zero, indicates that uniform recommendations will face divergent responses, requiring differentiated approaches or robust safety margins to account for the full spectrum of baseline household risk dispositions."

}

